        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The intensity of the targeted CO(4-3) line can be estimated from  the  strength of the CO(3-2) transition that we already detected (0.75 Jy.km/s/beam) and assuming a range of typical CO Spectral Line Energy Distributions (SLED) as observed for galaxies at z~2.
Two configurations can be explored: (i) if the GRB host converts its cold gas reservoirs into stars at low efficiency (suggested by the sSFR of the source, which matches that of the Main Sequence of Star forming galaxies at z~2), we use the SLED derived from star-forming BzK-selected sources up to the CO(4-3) transition (E.Daddi, private comm.) ; (ii) if the host experiences starbursting conditions (another possible scenario given the presence of a GRB and the disturbed morphology of the system), then we consider the CO SLED measured in submillimeter-selected galaxies (Ivison et al. 2011, Bothwell et al. 2012). Among these 2 cases, the former is the most pessimistic one as it implies the lowest ratio of CO(4-3)/CO(3-2) in line intensity. We thus predict in the most conservative case a lower limit of ~0.5Jy.km/s/beam for the CO(4-3) transition line. Assuming a spectral resolution of ~50MHz and a line width of ~400km/s, a 5sigma sensitivity of 1.25mJy/beam is therefore required to reach our scientific goal (1sig=0.25mJy/beam). According to the "Control and Performance" ALMA tool, this will be achieved in 1.14h of observing time including overheads (note that more than 17h would be required to get similar sensitivity at IRAM Plateau de Bure).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
